"@TillMaas @letsencrypt @firefox They do not. It's not the concept. It's just that currently everyone can sniff the DNS queries, with HTTPS only the DNS server of choice knows them.
AFAIK you can adjust ‚Äì which server to use ‚Äì later, in Firefox (later?), at least with an about:config setting."

"@MarcelWaldvogel @TillMaas @letsencrypt @firefox It's DNS, so you *always* have to send the query to some server‚Ä¶ choose whichever you want, though.

Also your ISP does not need to see the DNS request (unless you use the ISP's DNS server). If you resolve it locally, you can even avoid the internet cafe seeing it."
"@TillMaas @letsencrypt @firefox Yes, what about them? Totally depends on your configuration, what you want, etc. Usually home users don't want internal hosts, AFAIK."

"@TillMaas @ValentinGosu @MarcelWaldvogel @letsencrypt @firefox As for testing stage, there are different ways how Firefox can do the requests. As for now, it AFAIK sends both requests i.e. does some "race checks". The whole thing is still in testing and an early thing, so‚Ä¶

More details: https://t.co/jUvdik0843 https://t.co/I7IKE9x5tq"
